In 383 A.D. Maximus seized the Empire of the West, and Ausonius' pupilj Gratiam, was done to death. The poet, as we have seen, was possibly detained for a while at Treves3 and the revolution seems to have profoundly affected him. A fragment (Epist. xx.) written at this period clearly shows the gloom and foreboding which had settled upon his spirits, and possibly checked for a time the flow of his poetic vein.
